👉 Nested try-catch

Nested try-catch in Java simply means placing one try-catch block inside another. This is useful when different parts of your code may throw different types of exceptions and you want to handle them separately.

Basic Idea
Inner try-catch → handles specific exceptions locally
Outer try-catch → acts as a backup (handles exceptions not caught inside)

Syntax :

try{
    try{
        }catch(Exp e){
        }
    }
catch(Exp e){
        }

Similarly , we can furthur nest try catch blocks inside the nested try catch blocks.

Sample Code :

public class NestedTryExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Outer try block

            int arr[] = {1, 2, 3};

            try {
                // Inner try block
                System.out.println(arr[5]); // ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
            } catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
                System.out.println("Inner catch: Array index is out of bounds");
            }

            try {
                int result = 10 / 0; // ArithmeticException
            } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
                System.out.println("Inner catch: Cannot divide by zero");
            }

        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Outer catch: Some exception occurred");
        }

        System.out.println("Program continues...");
    }
}

👉 How it works

1. Java first executes the inner try block
2. If an exception occurs:
    It checks the nearest catch (inner one)
    If matched → handled there
3. If not handled inside:
    It goes to the outer catch block
4. Program continues after handling

👉 Key Points

1. Inner try-catch is used for fine-grained error handling
2. Outer try-catch is used for general or fallback handling
3. You can nest multiple levels, but too much nesting makes code messy
4. Always catch specific exceptions first, then general ones

